  "prompt": "How are septums pierced?",
  "response": "Septum piercing involves creating a hole in the thin piece of tissue that separates the nostrils, known as the septum. Here's how the process typically unfolds:\n\n1. **Consultation**: Before the piercing, the piercer will discuss the process, aftercare, and any concerns you might have. It's important to choose a professional with experience in body piercings.\n\n2. **Preparation**: The piercer will cleanse the area with an antiseptic solution to minimize the risk of infection. \n\n3. **Marking**: The piercer will use a skin-safe marker to mark the desired placement of the piercing on your septum. It\u2019s essential that you are comfortable with the location before proceeding.\n\n4. **Clamping**: A specialized clamp or forceps may be used to hold the septum in place, ensuring accuracy and stability during the puncture.\n\n5. **Piercing**: The piercer will use a sterile needle to create the hole. This is typically done quickly to minimize discomfort. It\u2019s essential that a single-use, disposable needle is used for hygiene purposes.\n\n6. **Inserting Jewelry**: Once the hole is created, the piercer will insert a small piece of jewelry, usually a circular barbell or septum ring, into the new piercing.\n\n7. **Aftercare Instructions**: After the piercing, the piercer will provide aftercare instructions to help ensure proper healing. This may include recommendations on cleaning the area with saline solution, avoiding touching the piercing with dirty hands, and keeping it free from makeup or other cosmetic products.\n\n8. **Healing**: A septum piercing typically takes about 6 to 8 weeks to heal, but full healing can take longer. Regular cleaning and care are essential during this period.\n\nIt's vital to ensure the piercing is done in a safe, clean environment and by a trained professional to avoid complications.",
